For planning purposes, Energy Transfer has considered the impact of worst case and alternative release scenarios.  The probability of the worst case catastrophic event evaluated in this report is extremely remote. The worst case scenario is far less probable than natural catastrophes that could produce much more severe and extensive damage and injury. A consideration of the release scenarios has been incorporated into Energy Transfer's notification and emergency response planning. Energy Transfer also considered the impact of a more likely loss of containment. 



Energy Transfer has not had any covered process incidents in the past five years. Energy Transfer has implemented safety precautions and procedures designed to prevent and mitigate catastrophic releases. Energy Transfer has active operating, maintenance, training and inspection procedures. Energy Transfer provides annual emergency response training to its employees. Energy Transfer's management is committed to the following:

- Preventing accidents;

- Continuing to proactively seek out improvements to process safety;

- Training employees in correct response procedures in the event of an accident;

- Participating in community emergency preparedness;

- Addressing any citizen concerns by fully explaining potential hazards associated with operations and all steps being taken to prevent and mitigate accidents; and

- Being a good corporate citizen in Butler County.



With these objectives in mind, the Risk Management Plan has been developed to provide information about our management of the risks associated with this Plant. Most important, Energy Transfer stresses our commitment to ensuring a safe operation for our employees, our visitors, and our community.
